AMSAT Village Session — 45 Minutes + Open Hack Time

"Building RADIANT: Amateur Delay-Tolerant Networking from Earth to Cislunar Space"

Audience (mixed — plan for this):

From the main talk:
  Software engineers who thought "I could help build that"
  Network engineers curious about DTN routing
  Makers who want to see real hardware
  Space enthusiasts who want more depth
  People who have never touched a radio but are intrigued

From the AMSAT Village:
  Satellite operators
  SDR developers
  Packet radio people
  CubeSat builders
  RF experimenters

The session must work for BOTH groups.

Don't assume amateur radio knowledge.
Don't assume networking ignorance.

Explain radio concepts briefly when they come up (KISS, TNC, 9600 baud).
Don't over-explain TCP, routing, or store-and-forward — the main talk covered that.

The tone is: "here's how we're actually building this, and here's how you can help."

---

Session Structure (45 minutes)

1. Welcome and Context (5 mins)

Acknowledge the mixed audience:

"Some of you are here because you saw the main talk and thought 'I want to know how that actually works.' Some of you live and breathe amateur radio and satellites. This session is for both of you."

Brief recap for newcomers (2 mins max):

The Internet breaks in space because of delay and disruption
DTN solves this with store-carry-forward
RADIANT is an amateur radio experiment to build and test this

Then set expectations:

"I'm going to show you the architecture, then we'll do two live demos — one simulating cislunar links, one over real radio hardware. After that, we'll open it up for hacking and discussion."

For the radio newcomers, promise:

"If I use a term you don't know, ask. There's no assumed knowledge here beyond 'I'm interested in networks.'"

2. RADIANT Architecture Deep Dive (10 mins)

Start with the "what" before the "how":

"We're building a system that can send a message from a ground station, through a relay satellite, to a lander on the Moon — using amateur radio and open-source software."

Position RADIANT in the bigger picture:

"In 2023, the Internet Society's Interplanetary Chapter — IPNSIG — published a framework for the Solar System Internet. Co-authored by Vint Cerf. Their recommendation: BPv7, LTP, and Contact Graph Routing as the basis for all communications beyond Earth. RADIANT implements exactly this architecture. We're not inventing a protocol stack; we're implementing the one that NASA, ESA, and the Internet Society have agreed on."

Then show the protocol stack:

┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
│   Application (bpsendfile, bping)   │
├─────────────────────────────────────┤
│   BPv7 (Bundle Protocol)            │  ← "Think of this as the envelope"
│   EID: dtn://callsign/service       │
├─────────────────────────────────────┤
│   LTP (Licklider Transmission)      │  ← "Reliable delivery over huge delays"
├─────────────────────────────────────┤
│   KISS (TNC Serial Framing)         │  ← "How we talk to the radio hardware"
├─────────────────────────────────────┤
│   USB Serial (TNC4)                 │  ← "A £100 modem"
├─────────────────────────────────────┤
│   G3RUH GFSK (9600 baud)            │  ← "The actual radio signal"
└─────────────────────────────────────┘

For the software people, explain:

BPv7 is like IP but for disrupted networks — bundles instead of packets
LTP is like TCP but designed for links where a round-trip takes minutes
KISS is just serial framing — bytes in, bytes out, no magic
The whole thing is open source, written in Go, C++, and Rust

Introduce Hardy (https://github.com/g4dpz/hardy):

Hardy is a modular Rust BPv7 implementation that I'm extending to support LTP.
It uses no_std core libraries — meaning it can run on bare-metal microcontrollers.
This makes it a candidate for actual flight software on a CubeSat.
"If you write Rust, this is where you can make a direct contribution to space hardware."

For the radio people, explain:

Why LTP over KISS directly (no AX.25) — AX.25 was designed for connected-mode links, DTN doesn't need that
Why callsign-embedded EIDs solve station identification without a separate beacon
  — The SSI report discusses BP identifier allocation (managed by IANA/SANA)
  — Amateur radio's existing callsign system is already globally unique and regulated
  — We've solved the "identifier governance" problem by leveraging what already exists
Why the system is DTN-engine-agnostic (HDTN, ION, µD3TN, Hardy)
  — HDTN for ground stations (high performance, C++)
  — Hardy for flight software (Rust, no_std, memory-safe, runs on microcontrollers)
  — The abstraction layer means you can swap engines via configuration
  — The SSI report emphasises interoperability between implementations — this is how we achieve it

Contact Graph Routing — for everyone:

"You know the satellite will be overhead at 14:32 tomorrow.
So you schedule the transmission now.
It's like a train timetable for data."

The "enforced openness" angle (this resonates with the EMF crowd):

Amateur radio regulations mean no encryption of user data
All protocols must be publicly documented
Everything we build is transparent and auditable by design
"This is a feature, not a limitation — it means anyone can inspect, verify, and contribute"

Link to the SSI security model:

The SSI report discusses BPSec — integrity and authenticity for bundles
For amateur radio, we use integrity protection (HMAC) without payload encryption
"We can prove who sent a bundle and that it hasn't been tampered with — we just can't hide what's inside it"
This aligns with the SSI report's recommendation: "authenticity of the bundle source can be provided by digital signatures" — we do exactly that
The report also notes that security policies should be transparent and published — amateur radio regulations already enforce this

3. Demo 1: Cislunar Simulation — Live (15 mins)

This is the centrepiece.

Setup:

Laptop running the 3-node HDTN simulation
Terminal windows showing all three nodes
Projector or large screen

The simulation:

Ground Station (Earth) → Lunar Orbiter (relay) → Lunar Lander
     nodeId=10              nodeId=20              nodeId=30

Live demonstration sequence:

a) Earth-Moon (1.3s one-way light time)

Send a file from Earth to the Lander:

  echo 'Hello Moon from EMF Camp!' > /tmp/hdtn-send/emf.dat
  bpsendfile --my-uri-eid=ipn:1.1 --dest-uri-eid=ipn:3.1 ...

Show:

The bundle leaving Earth
The 1.3-second propagation delay (real, via udp-delay-sim)
The bundle arriving at the orbiter relay
Store-and-forward at the relay
The bundle arriving at the lander
LTP acknowledgement returning 2.6 seconds later

Narrate what's happening at each stage. The audience can see the delay in real time.

b) Mars scenario (3-minute one-way)

Switch to Mars contact plan configuration.

Send a bundle and explain:

"This bundle is now in flight. It won't arrive for 3 minutes.
The sending node is responsible for it until the relay confirms receipt.
If we don't get an acknowledgement, it retransmits."

You don't need to wait the full 3 minutes — explain the principle, show the timer counting, then skip ahead to the received file.

c) Contact window demonstration

Show what happens when a contact window closes mid-transfer:

Bundle gets stored at the relay
Relay holds it until the next contact window opens
Then forwards it onward

This demonstrates the "postal service" model in action.

4. Demo 2: Radio Integration — Live or Prepared (10 mins)

Option A: Live RF demo (if equipment available)

Equipment:

Two laptops
Two Mobilinkd TNC4 units
Two handheld radios (Baofeng/FT-817) on a simplex frequency
Short antenna (rubber duck is fine indoors)

Show:

Send a DTN bundle from laptop A → TNC → radio → radio → TNC → laptop B
The KISS framing on the wire
The callsign appearing in the bundle metadata
The bundle arriving at the destination

This proves it works over real RF, not just simulation.

Option B: Pre-recorded RF demo (safer for timing)

Screen recording of the above, with audio of the 9600 baud modem tones.

Play the recording and narrate:

"This is what 9600 baud G3RUH sounds like"
"Here's the KISS frame being sent to the TNC"
"And here's the bundle arriving at the other end"

Even the audio of the modem tones is compelling for this audience.

Option C: Loopback with real TNC hardware

If RF is impractical in the venue:

Connect two TNCs back-to-back via audio cable
Same demo without radiating
Still shows the real hardware path

5. Roadmap and What's Next (5 mins)

The SSI report describes an evolution:

Today: Space agency point-to-point links
Transitional: Commercial and amateur networks emerge alongside agency backbones
Future: Multiple interconnected networks, peering like ISPs on Earth

RADIANT sits in the "transitional" phase — we're building an amateur SSI node before the commercial ones exist. The report calls for multistakeholder governance. Amateur radio operators are a stakeholder. RADIANT is how we earn our seat at that table.

Phase 1 — Terrestrial Radio (now)
  DTN over amateur packet radio links
  What we've demonstrated today

Phase 1.5 — QO-100
  DTN via geostationary amateur satellite (Es'hail-2)
  2.4 GHz up / 10 GHz down
  Real 240ms GEO delay
  "Who here has a QO-100 station?"

Phase 2 — CubeSat Engineering Model
  Flight-representative hardware on the ground
  STM32U585 + SDR
  µD3TN or Hardy as flight software
  Hardy is the Rust option — no_std, memory-safe, LTP support being added now
  "This is where the code you write today could end up in orbit"

Phase 3 — LEO DTN Payload
  First amateur DTN node in orbit
  437 MHz UHF
  Store-and-forward from orbit

Phase 4 — Cislunar DTN Node
  Amateur relay near the Moon
  S-band 500 bps
  The long-term goal
  The SSI report: "The infrastructure built in cislunar will become the scaffold for humans and robots to extend even farther"

Show the multi-node contact graph:

Multiple ground stations
LEO satellite passes
GEO backbone via QO-100
Cislunar link

The SSI vision: a "network of networks" in space.
RADIANT could be one of those networks — an amateur DTN network that peers with agency networks via standard BP/LTP.
Like early ISPs peering with university networks in the 1990s.

