Open Hack Session (after the 45-minute talk)

This is where the real recruitment happens.

Format: Informal, no fixed end time. People come and go.

Activities:

a) "Run a node" workshop

Bring 2-3 Raspberry Pis pre-configured with HDTN
Let people send bundles between them
Provide a one-page quickstart guide
QR code to the GitHub repo

b) Hands-on hardware

Mobilinkd TNC4 units people can handle
Show the KISS framing on an oscilloscope or logic analyser
Let people plug in and send a bundle

c) Architecture walkthrough

Print or display the system architecture diagram
Walk interested people through the code structure
Show the Go orchestrator, the C++ KISS CLA plugin, the configs

Hardy deep-dive for Rust developers:

Show the Hardy repo (https://github.com/g4dpz/hardy)
Explain the no_std architecture — core libraries compile for bare metal
Walk through the LTP implementation work in progress
Show how it targets STM32U585 (the CubeSat flight processor)
"This is real flight software. If you contribute here, your code could orbit Earth."

Good first issues for Rust contributors:
  LTP session management
  KISS framing integration
  Bundle serialisation optimisation
  no_std testing on embedded targets

d) Recruitment board

Physical sign-up sheet or digital form (QR code).

Explicitly list roles for BOTH audiences:

Software people:
  "I can write Go"
  "I can write C++"
  "I can write Rust" (Hardy — flight software, LTP, no_std)
  "I can help with CI/CD and testing"
  "I can build a web dashboard"
  "I want to work on the contact graph routing"
  "I want to contribute but don't know where to start"

Radio/hardware people:
  "I have a QO-100 station"
  "I have SDR experience"
  "I have CubeSat experience"
  "I can run a ground station node"
  "I can help with RF design"
  "I have a ham licence and want to get involved"

No licence required for most contributions:
  "You don't need a radio licence to write code, build simulations, or design protocols. You only need one to transmit."

Capture names, callsigns (if any), email addresses, GitHub handles.

e) Discussion topics to seed

"Should we keep AX.25 or go pure KISS?"
"What's the minimum viable QO-100 ground station for DTN?"
"How do we handle authentication without encryption?" (link to BPSec and the SSI security model)
"What would you build on top of a delay-tolerant network?"
  — Lunar BBS?
  — Sensor networks?
  — DTN messaging app?
  — Space weather data relay?
"How should amateur DTN nodes peer with agency networks?" (the SSI report's interconnection model)
"What governance model should an amateur SSI network use?" (multistakeholder, open standards, transparent policies)
"How do we handle time synchronisation for contact plans across multiple ground stations?" (the SSI report's time standards discussion)

f) Lightning talks (if time/interest)

Offer 5-minute slots for anyone who's done related work:

Packet radio operators
LoRa mesh experimenters
Satellite ground station builders
Anyone who's played with HDTN or ION

