---

Success Criteria

The session is a success if:

1. At least 5 people sign up to contribute in some capacity
2. Someone without a radio licence asks "how do I get involved?"
3. Someone asks "can I run a node from home?"
4. The live demo works without crashing (have backups!)
5. At least one good technical discussion happens organically
6. Someone with QO-100 experience offers to help with Phase 1.5
7. People are still hanging around the hack session an hour after the talk ends
8. A software person and a radio person start talking to each other about the project

---

Pattern: Inspire in the talk, recruit in the village.

The main talk attracts people who are intrigued by the idea.

The AMSAT Village session is where the genuinely interested technical audience self-selects and comes to talk to you.

That's a pattern that works very well at EMF.

